title: ‘Who knows what they’ve agreed to’: Labor does deal with Greens on environmental laws
description: Liberal Senator Andrew Bragg says the Coalition intended to do a deal with the government on environmental laws if there were reasonable accommodations.  “It’s very hard to negotiate with a party if they are not prepared to provide you with the details,” Mr Bragg told Sky News Australia.  “They’re going to guillotine this bill through this afternoon.”

title: ‘Pay a very steep price’: Trump’s warning to Washington DC shooter
description: United States President Donald Trump has posted on Truth Social following a recent shooting near the White House.   “The animal that shot two National Guardsmen, with both being critically wounded, and now in two separate hospitals, is also severely wounded, but regardless, will pay a very steep price,” Mr Trump said.

title: Man pleads guilty to ramming car into Liverpool FC trophy parade
description: A man has pleaded guilty to 31 offences after deliberately driving into crowds at a parade in Liverpool during a Premier League victory parade.  134 people were injured in the attack, with some thrown into the air or trapped underneath his car.  The judge said a lengthy custodial term should be expected when he is sentenced next month.

title: Malcolm Turnbull’s portrait unveiled in Canberra
description: Former prime minister Malcolm Turnbull’s portrait has been unveiled in Canberra with Prime Minister Anthony Albanese in attendance.

title: Victorian government to apologise to First Nations people for colonisation
description: The Victorian government will make an apology to First Nations people.  A media release by the state government says the apology will be made to First Nations people for the harm inflicted upon them through the actions and inactions of the state and the colony that came before it.  The apology is a key recommendation of Victoria's Yoorrook Justice Commission and was agreed to in the first statewide treaty, recently signed into law.

title: Over 50,000 illegal migrants shockingly missing in the UK, leaked documents reveal
description: Over 53,000 illegal migrants are reportedly missing across the United Kingdom, new leaked documents have revealed.  According to The Telegraph, a document named “absconder pool” suggested that as of October 2025, 53,298 are missing.  The document revealed that of the over 53,000 missing migrants, many breached their immigration bail or escaped from detention centres.  The Telegraph reported on data that revealed a further 736 migrant criminals absconded or were missing following their release from prison or detention.  A majority of the criminal migrants from prisons and detention facilities that are missing were reportedly facing deportation.

title: 'Categorically false': Meghan Markle refutes claim she stole $1,695 dress
description: Duchess of Sussex Meghan Markle has denied claims she kept a dress from a photoshoot without approval.  Meghan, who originally wore the $1,695 dress for her variety cover shoot back in 2022, was seen wearing the same dress in her new Netflix special.  The trailer posted for ‘With Love, Meghan: Holiday Celebration’ sparked a vast speculation across the media over whether she had taken the gown without permission.  A spokesperson for Meghan has spoken out about the reports, labelling them as “categorically false”.  “The insinuation that any items were taken without the full knowledge and agreement of the on-set stylists or their respective teams is not only categorically false, but also highly defamatory,” the spokesperson said.  “Any items kept were done so in total transparency and in accordance with contractual arrangements.”

title: Harry and Meghan set to be ‘left out in the cold’ during Royal Family’s US visit
description: UK barrister and broadcaster Andrew Eborn claims Prince Harry and Meghan Markle are set to be “left out in the cold” during the Royal Family’s visit to the US next year.   “They have been invited for this state visit, and they’re gearing up for this star-spangled trip to celebrate the 250th birthday,” Mr Eborn told Sky News Digital Presenter Gabriella Power.  “But Prince Harry and Meghan Markle are set to be left out in the cold … basically because they are no longer working Royals.  “The Declaration on Independence, while they declare themselves independent from the working Royals.  “You can guarantee we’re going to hear all about it.”

title: ‘Dirty deal’: Labor-Greens alliance ‘back in business’ on final day of parliament
description: Opposition Leader Sussan Ley has reacted to a recent environmental reform deal struck between the Labor Party and the Greens.  “The Labor-Greens alliance, which is back, back in business and working against communities, interests in industries for the future, against jobs and most importantly, working against lower power prices, Ms Ley said.  “A dirty deal between the Labor Party and the Greens, a deal that wasn’t necessary to conclude today or this year.  “This is going to put energy prices up and provide further pressure on electricity bills.”

title: Princess Catherine praised for ‘powerful’ statement spotlighting addiction issues
description: UK barrister and broadcaster Andrew Eborn reacts to Princess Catherine making a “powerful” personal statement showing support for people battling addiction.   “I love this when people in the public eye can use their position to share and shine a spotlight on things that affect lots and lots of people,” Mr Eborn told Sky News Digital Presenter Gabriella Power.  “What’s really good is she’s been returning to these Royal duties since she stepped away from the spotlight briefly to deal with her cancer battle.   “Well done her for shining a spotlight on that.”

title: UK council to rename street named after disgraced Andrew Mountbatten-Windsor
description: UK barrister and broadcaster Andrew Eborn reacts to a council in Northern Ireland changing the name of a street named after Andrew Mountbatten-Windsor.   “They began work to change the name, lots of residents complained, saying we don’t want it to be called Prince Andrew Way,” Mr Eborn told Sky News Digital Presenter Gabriella Power.  “What they have warned about is there will be these changes, but there will be those sorts of impacts … a bureaucratic nightmare.  “There are a few Prince Andrew Ways around the UK, and all of those are currently revising what they should call it.”

title: Princess Kate warns smartphones are ‘wrecking’ parent-child bonds
description: UK barrister and broadcaster Andrew Eborn weighs in on Princess Catherine’s warning that phones are “wrecking” parent-child bonds.   “People are addicted, and what she’s saying is that phones are sort of wrecking parent-childhood bonds,” Mr Eborn told Sky News Digital Presenter Gabriella Power.  “She said more evidence is needed about what causes people to turn to digital devices rather than engaging in family life.   “The more we can make sure people are not digitally dependent, the better. So well done, Princess Catherine.”

title: ‘She is not happy’: Fergie's financial troubles could lead to bombshell interview
description: UK barrister and broadcaster Andrew Eborn weighs in on reports Sarah Ferguson is tipped to take part in a bombshell interview amid controversy surrounding her ties to Jeffrey Epstein.  “I think if you offered her a lot of money, she would come and sit with us next week,” Mr Eborn told Sky News Digital Presenter Gabriella Power.  “She’s certainly not happy … but clearly money is going to be an issue, it always has been with Fergie.  “She’s in a terrible state at the moment … both mentally, which is awful, but also financially, so there is talk that a number of people are sort of swirling around her because she needs the cash.”

title: Afghan man identified as alleged Washington DC shooter as two guards remain in critical condition
description: The alleged shooter of two National Guardsmen near the White House has been identified as 29-year old Rahmanullah Lakanwal who arrived in the US in 2021

title: Barnaby Joyce would ‘thrash his legacy’ with One Nation defection
description: Nationals Senate Leader Bridget McKenzie claims Barnaby Joyce’s legacy “would be thrashed” if he defects to One Nation.  “Does he want to be part of a party of government to get things done,” Ms McKenzie told Sky News Australia.  “Or join a protest party where you won’t be able to do that type of thing.”
